{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LjXoEbAFDzkT3Br7tuXS9p","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: \"PRD-216\"\n3\ttitle: \"Canonicalize PRD list fields to reduce diff churn\"\n4\tkind: task\n5\tstatus: done\n6\tpriority: medium\n7\teffort: s\n8\tcapability: simple\n9\tparent: null\n10\tdepends_on:\n11\t  - \"[[PRD-214-frontmatter-roundtrip-drift]]\"\n12\tblocks: []\n13\timpacts:\n14\t  - src/darkfactory/prd.py\n15\t  - src/darkfactory/cli.py\n16\t  - tests/test_prd.py\n17\t  - tests/test_cli_normalize.py\n18\tworkflow: null\n19\ttarget_version: null\n20\tcreated: 2026-04-08\n21\tupdated: '2026-04-08'\n22\ttags:\n23\t  - harness\n24\t  - hygiene\n25\t---\n26\t\n27\t# Canonicalize PRD list fields to reduce diff churn\n28\t\n29\t## Summary\n30\t\n31\tPRD frontmatter contains several list fields (`depends_on`, `blocks`, `tags`, `impacts`) that have no semantic ordering — they're set-like. When two different agents or workflow runs touch the same field they can produce the same logical content in different orders, causing spurious diffs and merge conflicts.\n32\t\n33\tAdd a canonical ordering for each list field and a helper that any harness-driven mutation goes through, so the on-disk representation is stable and deterministic. Leave manual edits alone unless the user opts into normalization.\n34\t\n35\t## Motivation\n36\t\n37\tToday, an agent that adds `PRD-072` to an epic's `blocks:` field can produce either:\n38\t\n39\t```yaml\n40\tblocks:\n41\t  - \"[[PRD-070]]\"\n42\t  - \"[[PRD-071]]\"\n43\t  - \"[[PRD-072]]\"\n44\t```\n45\t\n46\tor:\n47\t\n48\t```yaml\n49\tblocks:\n50\t  - \"[[PRD-072]]\"\n51\t  - \"[[PRD-070]]\"\n52\t  - \"[[PRD-071]]\"\n53\t```\n54\t\n55\tdepending on what order it constructed the list. Both are equivalent, but the diff is noisy and a second run would re-shuffle it. Multiply by all the planning workflow runs and the dev-PRD directory accumulates churn that obscures real changes.\n56\t\n57\t## Requirements\n58\t\n59\t1. Each known list field has a documented canonical order:\n60\t   - `tags` — alphabetical (case-insensitive)\n61\t   - `impacts` — alphabetical by path string\n62\t   - `depends_on`, `blocks` — natural-sort by PRD ID (the same sort `prd status` uses), with the wikilink wrapping preserved\n63\t2. A helper `normalize_list_field_at(path, field, items)` accepts a list, applies the canonical sort for that field, and rewrites only the lines belonging to that field on disk — preserving everything else byte-for-byte (same invariant as `update_frontmatter_field_at`).\n64\t3. A subcommand `prd normalize [<PRD-ID> | --all]` runs the normalization across one or all PRDs as a one-shot cleanup. Reports how many files changed.\n65\t4. Manual single-line edits to other frontmatter fields are unaffected — the helper only touches the specified list field.\n66\t5. The helper is invoked from any harness builtin that mutates list fields (none today; future PRD-220 graph execution may introduce some).\n67\t\n68\t## Technical Approach\n69\t\n70\t### Sort keys\n71\t\n72\tReuse the existing sort key infrastructure:\n73\t\n74\t```python\n75\tfrom .prd import parse_id_sort_key\n76\t\n77\tCANONICAL_SORTS: dict[str, Callable[[str], object]] = {\n78\t    \"tags\": str.casefold,\n79\t    \"impacts\": lambda s: s,\n80\t    \"depends_on\": _wikilink_sort_key,\n81\t    \"blocks\": _wikilink_sort_key,\n82\t}\n83\t\n84\t\n85\tdef _wikilink_sort_key(item: str) -> tuple[int, ...]:\n86\t    \"\"\"Sort key for ``[[PRD-X-slug]]`` strings — extracts the ID and applies natural sort.\"\"\"\n87\t    inner = item.strip(\"[]\")\n88\t    prd_id = inner.split(\"-\", 2)[:2]  # [\"PRD\", \"4.2.1\"]\n89\t    return parse_id_sort_key(\"-\".join(prd_id))\n90\t```\n91\t\n92\t### Surgical list-field rewrite\n93\t\n94\tThe list-field analogue of `update_frontmatter_field_at` needs to handle multi-line values. Algorithm:\n95\t\n96\t1. Locate the field's header line (e.g. `^blocks:`).\n97\t2. Walk forward, consuming lines that match the YAML list-item indent pattern (`^  - ` or similar).\n98\t3. Replace the consumed range with the sorted items in the same indent style.\n99\t4. Leave the rest of the file alone.\n100\t\n101\tLimitations: only works for block-style lists (`- item` on its own line), not flow-style (`[a, b]`). The harness's PRDs all use block style so this is fine.\n102\t\n103\t### `prd normalize` subcommand\n104\t\n105\t```\n106\tprd normalize PRD-070       # one PRD\n107\tprd normalize --all         # every PRD in the dir\n108\tprd normalize --all --check # exit non-zero if any would change\n109\t```\n110\t\n111\t`--check` makes it CI-friendly.\n112\t\n113\t## Acceptance Criteria\n114\t\n115\t- [ ] AC-1: `normalize_list_field_at` sorts a `tags` field alphabetically and writes only the field's lines.\n116\t- [ ] AC-2: `normalize_list_field_at` sorts `blocks` by natural PRD ID order (`PRD-1.2` before `PRD-1.10`).\n117\t- [ ] AC-3: Other frontmatter fields and the body are byte-identical after normalization.\n118\t- [ ] AC-4: `prd normalize PRD-X` reports \"no changes\" when the file is already canonical.\n119\t- [ ] AC-5: `prd normalize --all --check` exits non-zero on at least one drifted file in a fixture set, and zero on a canonical set.\n120\t- [ ] AC-6: Test covers flow-style list rejection (raise a clear error rather than silently mangling).\n121\t\n122\t## Open Questions\n123\t\n124\t- [ ] Should `prd normalize` also touch the `body` (e.g. acceptance-criteria ordering)? Probably not — the body is the human's domain.\n125\t- [ ] Should the planning workflow auto-run normalize on every PRD it generates? Probably yes, as a final ShellTask.\n126\t- [ ] Wikilink slug extraction edge cases: does the sort key need the slug, or just the ID? Just the ID — natural sort uses `parse_id_sort_key`.\n127\t\n128\t## References\n129\t\n130\t- [[PRD-214-frontmatter-roundtrip-drift]] — same byte-preservation invariant\n131\t- [[PRD-220-graph-execution]] — first consumer that may need to mutate list fields\n132\t\n[result-id: r3]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01RgpQbWPMZNgKwdA9SZpuUD","session_id":"b6e45125-65ac-4a6b-991e-ec8e60826033","uuid":"1278d7ee-063d-4c7b-ae3c-418ddcb1b6eb","timestamp":"2026-04-09T03:05:38.274Z"}
